Note:
SwiftUI Parser - Builds AST from SwiftUI tokens

This file implements recursive descent parsing for SwiftUI declarative UI code.
Handles SwiftUI-specific constructs including view declarations, modifiers,
property wrappers, and state management.

SwiftUI AST Node Types:
- SWIFTUI_VIEW_STRUCT - View structure declaration (struct X: View)
- SWIFTUI_VIEW_BODY - View body property
- SWIFTUI_VIEW_CONTAINER - Container view (VStack, HStack, ZStack)
- SWIFTUI_VIEW_ELEMENT - Basic view element (Text, Button, Image, etc.)
- SWIFTUI_VIEW_MODIFIER - View modifier (.padding(), .background(), etc.)
- SWIFTUI_PROPERTY - Property declaration with wrapper (@State, @Binding)
- SWIFTUI_CLOSURE - Closure expression
- SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION - Swift expression

Features:
- Complete SwiftUI view structure parsing
- Property wrapper handling
- View modifier chains
- Trailing closure syntax
- State binding ($var) parsing
- Error reporting with position information
- Memory-safe AST construction

Dependencies:
- swiftui_lexer.runa (for tokenization)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/swiftui/swiftui_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SwiftUI AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant SWIFTUI_VIEW_STRUCT as Integer is 300
Constant SWIFTUI_VIEW_BODY as Integer is 301
Constant SWIFTUI_VIEW_CONTAINER as Integer is 302
Constant SWIFTUI_VIEW_ELEMENT as Integer is 303
Constant SWIFTUI_VIEW_MODIFIER as Integer is 304
Constant SWIFTUI_PROPERTY as Integer is 305
Constant SWIFTUI_CLOSURE as Integer is 306
Constant SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION as Integer is 307
Constant SWIFTUI_LITERAL as Integer is 308
Constant SWIFTUI_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 309

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SwiftUI AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Uniform AST node carrying everything any SwiftUI construct might need:
the discriminant (node_type), the source name (e.g. struct name or
modifier name), a literal/expression value, an optional property wrapper
(@State/@Binding), a type annotation, modifier and child lists, and a
parameters dictionary. A single struct simplifies tree walking and avoids
per-construct dispatch tables.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Ten 8-byte slots, totalling 80 bytes:
node_type@0, name@8, value@16, wrapper@24, type_annotation@32,
modifiers@40, children@48, parameters@56, line@64, column@72.
@End Implementation

Type called "SwiftUINode":
    node_type as Integer        Note: SWIFTUI_* constant
    name as Integer             Note: View/property/identifier name
    value as Integer            Note: Literal value or expression
    wrapper as Integer          Note: Property wrapper name (@State, @Binding, etc.)
    type_annotation as Integer  Note: Type annotation (for properties)
    modifiers as Integer        Note: List of modifier nodes
    children as Integer         Note: List of child nodes
    parameters as Integer       Note: Dictionary of parameters/attributes
    line as Integer             Note: Line number in source
    column as Integer           Note: Column number in source
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SwiftUI Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recursive-descent parser state. Holds the lexer (so it can pull the next
token on demand) and the current token (so look-ahead and peek are O(1)
without resetting the lexer). Errors are accumulated into a heap-owned
error_message string with a boolean flag to make has_parse_error a single
field read.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte slots, 32 bytes total:
lexer@0, current_token@8, error_message@16, has_error@24.
@End Implementation

Type called "SwiftUIParser":
    lexer as Integer            Note: SwiftUI lexer
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor that primes the parser by pulling the first token from the
lexer during initialisation. Doing this here (rather than lazily on first
peek) means every other method can assume current_token is already
populated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes for the SwiftUIParser, zeroes current_token,
error_message and has_error, then calls next_token to populate
current_token. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_swiftui_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create SwiftUI parser with lexer

    Let parser_size be 32  Note: SwiftUIParser: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize parser state
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: current_token = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false

    Note: Advance to first token
    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Destructor that frees the heap-owned error_message string before freeing
the parser struct itself — set_parse_error allocates a copy of the
message, so failing to free it here would leak. Null parser is a no-op so
callers can destroy unconditionally.
@End Reasoning

Process called "destroy_swiftui_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy SwiftUI parser

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Free error message if exists
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pulls the next token from the lexer and stores it as the new
current_token. Returns the new token so callers that immediately need it
do not have to do a follow-up peek. Lexer is responsible for emitting
TOKEN_EOF when input is exhausted.
@End Reasoning

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming token-type peek. If current_token is 0 (parser
prematurely cleared or a synthetic state), returns TOKEN_EOF so caller
branches behave as at-end rather than dereferencing null.
@End Reasoning

Process called "peek_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current token type

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming peek of the current token's lexeme (the source text it
represents). Used to read identifiers, keyword text, and literal values
without advancing the cursor. Null current_token yields 0 — callers must
handle that or pair with peek_token_type first.
@End Reasoning

Process called "peek_token_lexeme" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current token lexeme

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8

    Return lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate variant of peek_token_type: 1 if current is expected_type, 0
otherwise. Cursor is never advanced. The dedicated predicate avoids the
caller having to remember to compare against peek_token_type — a frequent
source of mistakes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
SwiftUI uses many contextual keywords ("struct", "var", "body", "some",
"View") that the lexer emits as TOKEN_KEYWORD. To distinguish them we
must compare lexemes; this combines the type check and the string
comparison into one predicate.
@End Reasoning

Process called "check_parser_keyword" takes parser as Integer, keyword as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token is specific keyword

    Let is_keyword be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_KEYWORD from Lexer

    If is_keyword is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let match be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, keyword

    Return match
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hard consume with diagnostic: if current matches expected_type, advance
and return 1; otherwise record error_msg via set_parse_error and return
0. Differs from PHP-style consume which silently fails — SwiftUI grammar
has stricter punctuation requirements.
@End Reasoning

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect token of specific type, set error if mismatch

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is not equal to expected_type:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Keyword-variant of expect_token: consume current iff its lexeme matches
the given keyword string, otherwise record error_msg and return 0. Used
for required contextual keywords like "struct", "var", "body", "some",
"View".
@End Reasoning

Process called "expect_keyword" takes parser as Integer, keyword as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect specific keyword, set error if mismatch

    Let is_keyword be proc check_parser_keyword with parser, keyword

    If is_keyword is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records a parse error: copies the supplied message onto the heap (so the
caller's pointer can go out of scope safely), frees any previous error
message to prevent leaks when multiple errors fire, and flips the
has_error flag. The copy makes message lifetime independent of the
caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads slot 16 (previous error_message); if non-null, deallocates it.
Allocates msg_length+1 bytes for the new copy, copies message bytes,
writes a null terminator, then stores the new pointer at slot 16 and sets
slot 24 (has_error) to 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    Note: Free previous error if exists
    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Note: Copy error message into an owned null-terminated buffer
    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc string_substring from StringPrim with message, 0, msg_length

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-field read of the has_error flag. Cheaper than checking
error_message for null because flag updates are atomic w.r.t. error
reporting — the flag flips before the heap message is fully populated, so
this can be checked early.
@End Reasoning

Process called "has_parse_error" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if parser has error

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    Return has_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the heap-owned error_message string pointer for diagnostic
display. Caller must NOT free the pointer — the parser still owns it and
destroy_swiftui_parser will free it on teardown.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_error_message" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    Return error_message
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single allocation site for SwiftUINode so every walker sees identical 80-
byte shape regardless of node_type. All non-discriminant slots are zeroed
so subsequent set_node_* calls do not have to first check for stale
content.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 80 bytes, writes node_type at offset 0, and writes 0 to slots
8/16/24/32/40/48/56/64/72 (name, value, wrapper, type_annotation,
modifiers, children, parameters, line, column).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_swiftui_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create SwiftUI AST node

    Let node_size be 80  Note: SwiftUINode: 10 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: name = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: value = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: wrapper = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: type_annotation = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: modifiers = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: children = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0  Note: parameters = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0  Note: line = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, 0  Note: column = 0

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Defensive deep-copy of the name string into a fresh heap allocation
because the caller-supplied pointer is typically the lexeme of the
current token — the lexer recycles its buffer when the parser advances,
so a borrow would dangle. The AST node owns the copy.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_node_name" takes node as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node name (copies string)

    Let name_length be proc string_length from StringCore with name
    Let name_copy be proc string_substring from StringPrim with name, 0, name_length

    If name_copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name_copy

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Deep-copies the value string for the same lexer-buffer-recycling reason
as set_node_name. Used for string literals, numeric literal text, and
encoded expression markers like "$variable" or ".member" forms produced
by parse_expression.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_node_value" takes node as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node value (copies string)

    Let value_length be proc string_length from StringCore with value
    Let value_copy be proc string_substring from StringPrim with value, 0, value_length

    If value_copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value_copy

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Deep-copies the property wrapper name (e.g. "State", "Binding",
"ObservedObject"). Stored at offset 24 so HIR translation can distinguish
"@State var x" from "var x" without re-parsing.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_node_wrapper" takes node as Integer, wrapper as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node property wrapper (copies string)

    Let wrapper_length be proc string_length from StringCore with wrapper
    Let wrapper_copy be proc string_substring from StringPrim with wrapper, 0, wrapper_length

    If wrapper_copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, wrapper_copy

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Deep-copies the Swift type annotation string (e.g. "Int", "String",
"Color") into the node's type_annotation slot at offset 32. Property
nodes carry this so later HIR translation can derive the correct field
type.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_node_type_annotation" takes node as Integer, type_annotation as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node type annotation (copies string)

    Let type_length be proc string_length from StringCore with type_annotation
    Let type_copy be proc string_substring from StringPrim with type_annotation, 0, type_length

    If type_copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, type_copy

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lazy-initialised children list: most leaf nodes never have children, so
we avoid the cost of an empty list allocation by creating one only on
first append. The slot stores a List handle which add appends to in order
(declaration order matters for view hierarchies).
@End Reasoning

Process called "add_node_child" takes node as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to node's children list

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 48

    Note: Create children list if doesn't exist
    If children is equal to 0:
        Let new_children be proc create from List

        If new_children is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, new_children
        Set children to new_children
    End If

    proc add from List with children, child

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Same lazy-init pattern as add_node_child but for the modifiers list. Kept
separate so HIR translation can walk modifiers in chain order
(.padding().background()) independently of the child view tree.
@End Reasoning

Process called "add_node_modifier" takes node as Integer, modifier as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add modifier node to node's modifiers list

    Let modifiers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40

    Note: Create modifiers list if doesn't exist
    If modifiers is equal to 0:
        Let new_modifiers be proc create from List

        If new_modifiers is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, new_modifiers
        Set modifiers to new_modifiers
    End If

    proc add from List with modifiers, modifier

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stores the parameters dictionary handle directly (no copy) because the
dictionary is created by parse_view_parameters specifically for this node
and ownership transfers in. Differs from set_node_name which copies — the
dict is opaque so we cannot meaningfully shallow-copy keys/values.
@End Reasoning

Process called "set_node_parameters" takes node as Integer, parameters as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set node parameters dictionary

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, parameters

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: View Structure Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level production: parses `struct <Name>: View { properties... var
body: some View { ... } }`. SwiftUI's central abstraction — every UI
declaration is a View-conforming struct. The body is required exactly
once; properties may be omitted; @State/@Binding wrappers may appear in
any order with body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `struct`, captures the identifier as the node name, consumes
`:`, requires the `View` keyword, then loops between properties (any
member starting with `@`) and the body declaration (any member starting
with `var`) until `}`. Each property becomes a SWIFTUI_PROPERTY child;
the body becomes a SWIFTUI_VIEW_BODY child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_view_struct" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SwiftUI view structure (struct X: View)

    @Reasoning:
    SwiftUI views are defined as structs conforming to the View protocol.
    The struct contains properties (often with @State or @Binding wrappers)
    and a body property that returns the view hierarchy.

    Grammar:
    struct <name>: View {
        @State var property: Type
        var body: some View {
            view_hierarchy
        }
    }
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_VIEW_STRUCT

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expect 'struct' keyword
    Let success be proc expect_keyword with parser, "struct", "Expected 'struct' keyword"

    If success is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expect struct name
    Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_identifier is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected struct name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let struct_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with node, struct_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect colon
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer, "Expected ':' after struct name"

    Note: Expect 'View' protocol
    Let is_view be proc check_parser_keyword with parser, "View"

    If is_view is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'View' protocol conformance"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect opening brace
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{' to start struct body"

    Note: Parse struct body (properties and view body)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Check for closing brace
        Let is_rbrace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

        If is_rbrace is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Check for property wrapper (@State, @Binding, etc.)
        Let is_at be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_AT from Lexer

        If is_at is equal to 1:
            Let property be proc parse_property with parser

            If property is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            proc add_node_child with node, property
        Otherwise:
            Note: Check for 'var body'
            Let is_var be proc check_parser_keyword with parser, "var"

            If is_var is equal to 1:
                Let body be proc parse_view_body with parser

                If body is equal to 0:
                    Return 0
                End If

                proc add_node_child with node, body
            Otherwise:
                proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected property or view body"
                Return 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Expect closing brace
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}' to end struct body"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a wrapper-prefixed property declaration. The wrapper name is
required at this entry point (callers route here only after seeing
TOKEN_AT); the type annotation and initial value expression are both
optional, matching Swift's syntax which permits inference and uninitialised
fields.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `@`, captures the wrapper name as node.wrapper, then expects
`var` or `let`. Captures the property identifier as node.name. If `:`
follows, captures the type annotation; if `=` follows, parses the initial
value expression as a child. Errors propagate via set_parse_error.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_property" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse property with optional wrapper (@State var x: Int)

    @Reasoning:
    SwiftUI properties can have property wrappers like @State, @Binding, @ObservedObject.
    These wrappers provide special behaviors for state management and data flow.

    Grammar:
    @<Wrapper> var <name>: <Type> = <value>?
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_PROPERTY

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expect @ symbol
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_AT from Lexer, "Expected '@' for property wrapper"

    Note: Expect property wrapper name
    Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_identifier is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected property wrapper name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let wrapper_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_wrapper with node, wrapper_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect 'var' or 'let'
    Let is_var be proc check_parser_keyword with parser, "var"
    Let is_let be proc check_parser_keyword with parser, "let"

    If is_var is equal to 0:
        If is_let is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'var' or 'let'"
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect property name
    Let is_identifier2 be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_identifier2 is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected property name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let property_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with node, property_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Check for type annotation
    Let is_colon be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer

    If is_colon is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Expect type name
        Let is_type be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

        If is_type is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected type name"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let type_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_type_annotation with node, type_name
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for initial value
    Let is_equals be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_EQUALS from Lexer

    If is_equals is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Parse initial value expression
        Let value_expr be proc parse_expression with parser

        If value_expr is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc add_node_child with node, value_expr
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses the mandatory `var body: some View { ... }` declaration. The
"some View" opaque return type is recognised but not stored — we know
every body produces a View, so re-storing the type would be redundant.
The braced body becomes a single child built by parse_view_hierarchy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the keywords `var`, body identifier, `:`, `some`, `View` in
order, then `{`, then delegates the entire braced contents to
parse_view_hierarchy and attaches the result as the sole child of the
SWIFTUI_VIEW_BODY node. Finally consumes the closing `}`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_view_body" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse view body property (var body: some View)

    @Reasoning:
    The body property is required for all SwiftUI views. It returns the view hierarchy.
    The return type is 'some View' which is an opaque result type.

    Grammar:
    var body: some View {
        view_hierarchy
    }
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_VIEW_BODY

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expect 'var' keyword
    proc expect_keyword with parser, "var", "Expected 'var' keyword"

    Note: Expect 'body' identifier
    Let is_body be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer
    Let body_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    Let is_body_name be proc string_equals from StringCore with body_lexeme, "body"

    If is_body_name is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected 'body' identifier"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Expect colon
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer, "Expected ':' after body"

    Note: Expect 'some' keyword
    proc expect_keyword with parser, "some", "Expected 'some' keyword"

    Note: Expect 'View' keyword
    proc expect_keyword with parser, "View", "Expected 'View' type"

    Note: Expect opening brace
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{' to start body"

    Note: Parse view hierarchy
    Let view_hierarchy be proc parse_view_hierarchy with parser

    If view_hierarchy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc add_node_child with node, view_hierarchy

    Note: Expect closing brace
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}' to end body"

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: View Hierarchy Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-view-plus-modifier-chain producer. Parses one base view (container
or element) then greedily consumes any following `.modifier(...)` chain.
Modifier ordering matters semantically in SwiftUI (.padding().background
differs from .background().padding) so the chain is recorded in source
order on the base view's modifiers list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates the base to parse_base_view, then loops: while the next token
is TOKEN_DOT, consume it and call parse_modifier; attach each result via
add_node_modifier on the base. Loop terminates at any non-dot lookahead.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_view_hierarchy" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SwiftUI view hierarchy (containers, elements, modifiers)

    @Reasoning:
    SwiftUI views are composed hierarchically. Container views (VStack, HStack, ZStack)
    contain other views. Elements (Text, Button, Image) are leaf nodes.
    All views can have modifiers chained with dot notation.

    This function parses the view tree and modifier chains.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Parse base view (container or element)
    Let base_view be proc parse_base_view with parser

    If base_view is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse modifier chain
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_dot be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

        If is_dot is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Parse modifier
        Let modifier be proc parse_modifier with parser

        If modifier is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc add_node_modifier with base_view, modifier
    End While

    Return base_view
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatches the first token of a view expression to either
parse_container_view (VStack/HStack/ZStack — recognised by lexeme equality
since the lexer emits them as TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE), parse_element_view
(all other TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE values), or parse_element_view again
(TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, for user-defined views). Anything else is a parse
error.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_base_view" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse base view (container or element)

    @Reasoning:
    Base views can be:
    - Container views with trailing closures: VStack { ... }
    - Element views with parameters: Text("Hello")
    - Custom view instances: MyCustomView()
    @End Reasoning

    @Reasoning:
    A view name may be lexed either as TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE (the capitalised built-ins
    the lexer recognises) or as a plain TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (container types not in the
    lexer's built-in set such as List/ForEach/Group/ScrollView, plus user-defined
    views). The container-vs-element decision is made on the NAME, not the token
    class, so both branches capture the name and route through one shared
    container-name check. Container views own a trailing closure of child views;
    everything else is an element (which may still accept an optional trailing
    closure such as a Button action).
    @End Reasoning
    Let is_view_type be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE from Lexer
    Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_view_type is equal to 0:
        If is_identifier is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected view type or identifier"
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let view_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Container views own a trailing closure of children. Recognise the
    Note: full set of SwiftUI structural containers by name.
    Let is_container be 0
    Let is_vstack be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "VStack"
    If is_vstack is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_hstack be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "HStack"
    If is_hstack is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_zstack be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "ZStack"
    If is_zstack is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_list be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "List"
    If is_list is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_foreach be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "ForEach"
    If is_foreach is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_group be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "Group"
    If is_group is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_scrollview be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "ScrollView"
    If is_scrollview is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_section be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "Section"
    If is_section is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_form be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "Form"
    If is_form is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_navview be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "NavigationView"
    If is_navview is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If
    Let is_navstack be proc string_equals from StringCore with view_name, "NavigationStack"
    If is_navstack is equal to 1:
        Set is_container to 1
    End If

    If is_container is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_container_view with parser, view_name
    End If

    Return proc parse_element_view with parser, view_name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Container views (VStack/HStack/ZStack) have two distinguishing features:
optional parenthesised configuration parameters (alignment, spacing) and
a mandatory trailing closure listing child views. Children are recursively
parsed by parse_view_hierarchy so each child can have its own modifier
chain.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Caller has already consumed the view-type token and supplied its name.
Optionally consumes `(parameters)` via parse_view_parameters, then
expects `{`. Loops parsing child view hierarchies until `}`. Each child
attaches via add_node_child in source order.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_container_view" takes parser as Integer, container_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse container view with trailing closure (VStack { ... })

    @Reasoning:
    Container views like VStack, HStack, ZStack use trailing closure syntax
    to define their child views. They can also have parameters like alignment
    and spacing before the closure.

    Grammar:
    VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 10) {
        child_views
    }
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_VIEW_CONTAINER

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc set_node_name with node, container_name

    Note: Check for parameters
    Let is_lparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

    If is_lparen is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Parse parameters
        Let parameters be proc parse_view_parameters with parser

        If parameters is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc set_node_parameters with node, parameters

        Note: Expect closing paren
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after parameters"
    End If

    Note: Expect opening brace (trailing closure)
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{' for trailing closure"

    Note: Parse child views
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_rbrace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

        If is_rbrace is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Let child_view be proc parse_view_hierarchy with parser

        If child_view is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc add_node_child with node, child_view
    End While

    Note: Expect closing brace
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}' to end trailing closure"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Element views (Text/Image/Button/etc. plus user-defined views) have
parameters but most do NOT take a child closure. The notable exception is
Button(label, action:), so we still accept an optional trailing `{ ...
}` closure and attach it as a child if present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Caller has already consumed the identifier and supplied its name.
Optionally consumes `(parameters)`, then optionally consumes a trailing
`{ ... }` closure via parse_closure (attached as a child rather than a
modifier — actions ARE the value of the view, not transformations of it).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_element_view" takes parser as Integer, element_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse element view with parameters (Text("Hello"))

    @Reasoning:
    Element views like Text, Button, Image take parameters to configure them.
    Parameters can be literals, expressions, or closures.

    Grammar:
    Text("Hello")
    Button("Click me") { action }
    Image(systemName: "star")
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_VIEW_ELEMENT

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc set_node_name with node, element_name

    Note: Check for parameters
    Let is_lparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

    If is_lparen is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Parse parameters
        Let parameters be proc parse_view_parameters with parser

        If parameters is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc set_node_parameters with node, parameters

        Note: Expect closing paren
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after parameters"
    End If

    Note: Check for trailing closure (for Button, etc.)
    Let is_lbrace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer

    If is_lbrace is equal to 1:
        Let closure be proc parse_closure with parser

        If closure is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc add_node_child with node, closure
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Caller has already consumed the leading `.`. We then parse an identifier
(the modifier name) and optional parenthesised parameter list. Modifier
parameters use the same syntax as view parameters so we delegate to
parse_view_parameters for consistency.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_modifier" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse view modifier (.padding(), .background(), etc.)

    @Reasoning:
    View modifiers are chained using dot notation. They can take parameters
    or be parameterless. Modifiers can also be chained.

    Grammar:
    .padding()
    .padding(20)
    .background(Color.red)
    .foregroundColor(.blue)
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_VIEW_MODIFIER

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expect modifier name
    Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_identifier is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected modifier name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let modifier_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_name with node, modifier_name
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Check for parameters
    Let is_lparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

    If is_lparen is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Parse parameters
        Let parameters be proc parse_view_parameters with parser

        If parameters is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc set_node_parameters with node, parameters

        Note: Expect closing paren
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after modifier parameters"
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parameter Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Unified parameter parser for view constructors and modifier calls. Swift
allows positional, named, and mixed argument lists; we encode all three
into a single Dictionary keyed either by parameter name (named) or
stringified index (positional). This avoids needing a separate ordered
list and a names map.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks `name: value` or bare `value` arguments separated by commas. For
named parameters the identifier-then-colon lookahead is performed by
consuming the identifier first and then checking for `:`; if no colon
follows, the consumed identifier is treated as a positional identifier
expression. param_index is incremented only for positional arguments.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_view_parameters" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse view/modifier parameters

    @Reasoning:
    Parameters can be:
    - Positional: Text("Hello")
    - Named: Image(systemName: "star")
    - Mixed: Button("Click", action: { ... })

    We store them in a dictionary with either index or name as key.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parameters be proc create from Dict

    If parameters is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let param_index be 0

    Note: Check for empty parameters
    Let is_rparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

    If is_rparen is equal to 1:
        Return parameters
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Check for named parameter (name: value)
        Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

        If is_identifier is equal to 1:
            Let next_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
            proc advance_token with parser

            Note: Check if this is a named parameter (identifier followed by colon)
            Let is_colon be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COLON from Lexer

            If is_colon is equal to 1:
                proc advance_token with parser

                Note: Parse parameter value
                Let value be proc parse_expression with parser

                If value is equal to 0:
                    Return 0
                End If

                Note: Store with name as key
                proc set from Dict with parameters, next_lexeme, value
            Otherwise:
                Note: This was a positional parameter (identifier expression)
                Note: Need to create identifier node for it
                Let id_node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_IDENTIFIER

                If id_node is equal to 0:
                    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
                    Return 0
                End If

                proc set_node_name with id_node, next_lexeme

                Note: Store with index as key
                Let index_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with param_index
                proc set from Dict with parameters, index_str, id_node
                Set param_index to param_index plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Parse positional parameter value
            Set value to proc parse_expression with parser

            If value is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: Store with index as key
            Set index_str to proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with param_index
            proc set from Dict with parameters, index_str, value
            Set param_index to param_index plus 1
        End If

        Note: Check for comma (more parameters)
        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Return parameters
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Minimal Swift expression parser sufficient for SwiftUI parameter values.
Recognises state bindings (`$variable`), string/number/boolean literals,
identifiers (with optional `(args)` calls and `.member` access), and
SwiftUI's shorthand member references (`.leading`, `.red`). Heavier Swift
expression grammar is out of scope — we only need what appears inside
parameter lists.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tagged dispatch on the leading token. `$` builds a SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION
with value "$name". String/number/boolean literals build SWIFTUI_LITERAL
nodes carrying the lexeme. Identifiers are wrapped as SWIFTUI_IDENTIFIER
and may be promoted to SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION on detecting a `(call)` or
`.member` suffix. Leading `.` produces a `.member` SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse Swift expression

    @Reasoning:
    Expressions can be:
    - Literals (strings, numbers, booleans)
    - Identifiers
    - State bindings ($variable)
    - Member access (Color.red)
    - Function calls
    - Closures
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check for state binding ($variable)
    Let is_dollar be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOLLAR from Lexer

    If is_dollar is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Expect identifier
        Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

        If is_identifier is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected identifier after '$'"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let binding_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Create binding expression node
        Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Store as "$variable" format
        Let binding_str be proc string_concat from StringPrim with "$", binding_name
        proc set_node_value with node, binding_str

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Check for string literal
    Let is_string be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_STRING from Lexer

    If is_string is equal to 1:
        Let string_value be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Set node to proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_LITERAL

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        proc set_node_value with node, string_value

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Check for number literal
    Let is_number be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer

    If is_number is equal to 1:
        Let number_value be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Set node to proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_LITERAL

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        proc set_node_value with node, number_value

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Check for boolean literal
    Let is_boolean be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_BOOLEAN from Lexer

    If is_boolean is equal to 1:
        Let bool_value be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Set node to proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_LITERAL

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        proc set_node_value with node, bool_value

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier or member access (Color.red)
    Set is_identifier to proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_identifier is equal to 1:
        Let id_value be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Check for member access
        Let is_dot be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

        If is_dot is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser

            Note: Expect member name
            Let is_member be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

            If is_member is equal to 0:
                proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected member name after '.'"
                Return 0
            End If

            Let member_name be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
            proc advance_token with parser

            Note: Create member access expression
            Set node to proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION

            If node is equal to 0:
                proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
                Return 0
            End If

            Note: Store as "Type.member" format
            Let member_prefix be proc string_concat from StringPrim with id_value, "."
            Let member_str be proc string_concat from StringPrim with member_prefix, member_name
            proc set_node_value with node, member_str

            Return node
        End If

        Note: Check for function call
        Let is_lparen be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

        If is_lparen is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser

            Note: Parse function parameters
            Let parameters be proc parse_view_parameters with parser

            If parameters is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer, "Expected ')' after function parameters"

            Note: Create function call expression
            Set node to proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION

            If node is equal to 0:
                proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
                Return 0
            End If

            proc set_node_name with node, id_value
            proc set_node_parameters with node, parameters

            Return node
        End If

        Note: Simple identifier
        Set node to proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_IDENTIFIER

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        proc set_node_name with node, id_value

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Check for closure
    Let is_lbrace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer

    If is_lbrace is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_closure with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for dot-prefixed member (.leading, .blue)
    Let is_dot2 be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

    If is_dot2 is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Expect member name
        Let is_member2 be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

        If is_member2 is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected member name after '.'"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let member_name2 be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Create member reference expression (.leading)
        Set node to proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_EXPRESSION

        If node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Store as ".member" format
        Let member_str2 be proc string_concat from StringPrim with ".", member_name2
        proc set_node_value with node, member_str2

        Return node
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected expression"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a brace-delimited closure. The optional parameter form `name in
body` is detected by lookahead: identifier followed by `in` means we have
a parameter, otherwise the identifier was the first statement of an
implicit-parameter closure (the `it`/no-parameter form) and gets re-
emitted as a regular identifier child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes `{`. If the next token is an identifier, consume it and peek
for `in` — if matched, record it as node.name; otherwise wrap the
identifier as a child SWIFTUI_IDENTIFIER (no backtracking needed; we own
the lexeme). Then loops parse_closure_statement until `}`.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_closure" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse closure expression

    @Reasoning:
    Closures in SwiftUI can be:
    - Simple: { Text("Hello") }
    - With parameters: { value in Text(value) }
    - Trailing closures for Button actions, etc.
    @End Reasoning

    Let node be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_CLOSURE

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Expect opening brace
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{' to start closure"

    Note: Check for parameters (param in ...)
    Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_identifier is equal to 1:
        Let next_lexeme be proc peek_token_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Check for 'in' keyword
        Let is_in be proc check_parser_keyword with parser, "in"

        If is_in is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser

            Note: Store parameter name
            proc set_node_name with node, next_lexeme
        Otherwise:
            Note: No parameters, need to backtrack and parse as body
            Note: Create expression node for the identifier
            Let expr be proc create_swiftui_node with SWIFTUI_IDENTIFIER

            If expr is equal to 0:
                proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
                Return 0
            End If

            proc set_node_name with expr, next_lexeme
            proc add_node_child with node, expr
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse closure body (statements/expressions)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_rbrace be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

        If is_rbrace is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse statement/expression
        Let stmt be proc parse_closure_statement with parser

        If stmt is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc add_node_child with node, stmt
    End While

    Note: Expect closing brace
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}' to end closure"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A SwiftUI closure body is typically either a ViewBuilder (sequence of
view declarations) or a plain expression (action body). We disambiguate
by lookahead: TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER routes to
parse_view_hierarchy (most closures here are ViewBuilders); anything else
falls through to parse_expression.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_closure_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse closure statement

    @Reasoning:
    Closure statements can be:
    - View hierarchies (for ViewBuilder closures)
    - Swift statements (assignments, function calls)
    - Control flow (if, switch, for, etc.)
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check for view hierarchy (Text, VStack, etc.)
    Let is_view_type be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_VIEW_TYPE from Lexer

    If is_view_type is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_view_hierarchy with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for identifier (could be custom view or statement)
    Let is_identifier be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer

    If is_identifier is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_view_hierarchy with parser
    End If

    Note: Otherwise parse as expression
    Return proc parse_expression with parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public top-level entry. The current grammar targets a single primary view
struct per file (extensions and preview providers are intentionally
unimplemented at this layer because HIR translation does not yet
consume them). Errors recorded mid-parse short-circuit the return.
@End Reasoning

Process called "parse_swiftui" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse SwiftUI source file (top-level entry point)

    @Reasoning:
    SwiftUI files typically contain:
    - Import statements (optional)
    - View struct declarations
    - Extension declarations (optional)
    - Preview providers (optional)

    The view struct is the core declarative UI component in SwiftUI code.
    We parse the complete view struct including its body closure and all modifiers.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Parse view struct
    Let view_struct be proc parse_view_struct with parser

    If view_struct is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check for parse errors
    Let has_error be proc has_parse_error with parser

    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return view_struct
End Process
